{
    "identity": "nprot-2378",
    "title": "Production and regeneration of G. lucidum protoplasts",
    "content": [
        {
            "header": "Introduction",
            "content": "G.lucidum have two different types hypha in mycelium--the haploid one and the diploid one. Using a protoplast regeneration method can generate an isolate from a single cell which maybe only contain a suit of chromsomes. Firstly, we digest the mycelium into a single protoplast. Then, dilute the protoplast  suspension into an appropriate concentration. Third, regenerate these protoplasts on MYG medium."
        },
        {
            "header": "Reagents",
            "content": "Lywallzyme\r\n\n\nMannitol\r\n\n\nPDB broth\r\n\n\nMYG agar medium"
        },
        {
            "header": "Equipment",
            "content": "Shaker\r\n\n\nIncubator"
        },
        {
            "header": "Procedure",
            "content": "1. Inoculate mycelia into 100 ml PDB media \\(200 g potato, 20 g dextrose, 1 L water) in 250 ml flasks. \r\n  2. Cultivate the mycelia were cultivated in the dark at 28\u00b0C under continuous shaking at 50 rpm. \r\n  3. Harvest the culturesby filtering through sterile gauze.\r\n  4. Place approximately 5 g of mycelia in a 50 ml tube containing 20 ml of filter-sterilized 1.5% lywallzyme \\(Guangdong Institute of Microbiology, China) in 0.6 M mannitol. \r\n  5. Incubate the mixtureat 30\u00b0C for approximately 2 h with occasional agitation. \r\n  6. Remove hyphae fragments after 2 h of digestion. MYG agar medium \\(2% malt extract, 0.2% yeast extract, 2% dextrose, 1.5% agar) was used for G. lucidum protoplast regeneration. \r\n  7. Dilute the protoplast suspension was diluted to 1 x 10\n4\ncells/ml, and 50 \u00b5l of the diluted protoplast suspension was added to a MYG medium plate and inoculated at 25\u00b0C in the dark."
        }
    ],
